While I'm not a chemist, I am one of those unusual people who enjoyed organic chemistry in college. Lately, I've been reading up on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_table" rel="noopener" target="_blank">periodic table</a> on Wikipedia (who among us doesn't do this every 6-8 weeks?) and thought it would be interesting to develop a concise equation or program to directly determine the atomic number [latex]Z[/latex] of the [latex]k^{th}[/latex] noble gas, including hypothetical noble gases that don't exist. I claim no practical use for this exercise other than it seemed fun and somewhat educational. Chemistry-averse readers need not fear; this post is more about patterns and sums than about chemistry.

The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noble_gas" rel="noopener" target="_blank">noble gases</a>, so named because they are largely chemically inert, are the elements in the last group (last column) of the periodic table. Their general lack of chemical reactivity is due to their electron configuration, which comprises full, stable outer shells. The existing elements of this group (helium, neon, argon, krypton, xenon, radon, and oganesson) are listed in the table below, along with their atomic numbers [latex]Z[/latex] and chemical symbols. The index [latex]k[/latex], which appears in the title, is simply a variable I came up with to describe the location of each noble gas in the sequence. [latex]k=1[/latex] refers to helium since it's the first noble gas, [latex]k=2[/latex] refers to neon since it's the second noble gas, [latex]k=3[/latex] refers to argon since it's the third noble gas, and so on.

<h5>Table 1. Noble gases</h5>
