The table above also includes a row labeled [latex]\Delta Z[/latex], a quantity I use to describe the difference between the atomic number [latex]Z[/latex] of each element in the sequence with the previous element in the sequence. For example, xenon ([latex]k=5[/latex]) has atomic number [latex]Z=54[/latex] and the previous element in the sequence, krypton ([latex]k=4[/latex]), has atomic number [latex]Z=36[/latex]. [latex]54 - 36 = 18[/latex], so the value of [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] corresponding to xenon ([latex]k=5[/latex]) is 18. For the seven elements above, we can find the sequence of [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] values to be 2, 8, 8, 18, 18, 32, 32. Remember this sequence—it's important and will come up again.

The atomic number of an element is equal to the number of electrons surrounding the atom. Thus, the atomic number is directly related to the element's electron configuration. The electrons of an atom are grouped into <em>shells</em>, specifically into <em>subshells</em> within each shell. Each shell is described by the <em>principal quantum number</em> [latex]n[/latex]. [latex]n=1[/latex] would refer to the first shell, [latex]n=2[/latex] would refer to the second shell, and so on. Each shell has [latex]n[/latex] possible subshells, so the first shell ([latex]n=1[/latex]) has 1 subshell, the second shell ([latex]n=2[/latex]) has up to 2 subshells, the third shell ([latex]n=3[/latex]) has up to 3 subshells, and so on. Subshells are described by the <em>azimuthal quantum number</em> [latex]l[/latex], which begins at [latex]l=0[/latex]. Electrons fill shells and subshells in order of increasing energy, the details of which are beyond the scope of this post.

Each subshell [latex]l[/latex] can hold up to [latex]2(2l+1)[/latex] electrons, meaning that the first subshell ([latex]l=0[/latex]) contains up to 2 electrons, the second subshell ([latex]l=1[/latex]) contains up to 6 electrons, the third subshell ([latex]l=2[/latex]) contains up to 10 electrons, etc. You might know subshells by their more familiar letter designations: <em>s</em>, <em>p</em>, <em>d</em>, and <em>f</em>, where [latex]l=0[/latex] corresponds to <em>s</em>, [latex]l=1[/latex] corresponds to <em>p</em>, and so on. The table below displays the subshells (and the maximum number of electrons in each) for the first five shells.

<h5>Table 2. Shells and subshells</h5>
