The first shell ([latex]n=1[/latex]) has one subshell and a total of 2 electrons. The second shell ([latex]n=2[/latex]) has two subshells containing up to 2 + 6 = 8 electrons. The third shell ([latex]n=3[/latex]) has three subshells containing up to 2 + 6 + 10 = 18 electrons. The fourth shell ([latex]n=4[/latex]) has four subshells containing up to 2 + 6 + 10 + 14 = 32 electrons. Observe how these numbers—2, 8, 18, 32—are the same as the values from the [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] row in <a href="#table1">Table 1</a>. Remembering that there are [latex]2(2l+1)[/latex] electrons in a subshell [latex]l[/latex] and that a shell [latex]n[/latex] has [latex]n[/latex] subshells (numbered from [latex]l=0[/latex] to [latex]l=n-1[/latex]), we can write the total number of electrons [latex]e_n[/latex] in the [latex]n^{\text{th}}[/latex] shell as the sum of its subshells:

[latex]\displaystyle{e_n = \sum\limits_{l=0}^{n-1} 2(2l + 1)}[/latex]

Multiplying this out and evaluating the sums:

[latex]\displaystyle{e_n = \sum\limits_{l=0}^{n-1} {2(2l + 1)} = 4\sum\limits_{l=0}^{n-1} {l} + \sum\limits_{l=0}^{n-1} {2}}[/latex]
&nbsp;
[latex]\displaystyle{= 2n(n-1) + 2n}[/latex]
&nbsp;
[latex]\displaystyle{e_n = 2n^2}[/latex]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id="eqn1"><strong>(Equation 1)</strong></span>

Thus, there can be up to [latex]2n^2[/latex] electrons in each shell, which corresponds to the values of 2, 8, 18, 32, etc. Next, referring again to <a href="#table1">Table 1</a>, notice how we can split the elements into pairs with identical [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] values. For example, [latex]k=0[/latex] and [latex]k=1[/latex] would form the first pair. The second pair would include [latex]k=2[/latex] and [latex]k=3[/latex], both of which have [latex]\Delta Z = 8[/latex]. The third pair would consist of [latex]k=4[/latex] and [latex]k=5[/latex], which have [latex]\Delta Z = 18[/latex]. The fourth pair would be [latex]k=6[/latex] and [latex]k=7[/latex], which have [latex]\Delta Z = 32[/latex]. The only exception is the first pair with [latex]k=0[/latex], since that doesn't correspond to an actual element with a positive number of electrons, but the pattern remains otherwise unaffected. Let's number these pairs using the letter [latex]p[/latex]. The first pair, [latex]p=1[/latex], would contain [latex]k=0, 1[/latex]. The second pair, [latex]p=2[/latex], would contain [latex]k=2, 3[/latex]. You get the idea.

The first important thing to recognize here is that each pair has the same [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] value, as we just mentioned, and that the [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] value for each pair is the same as that given by <a href="#eqn1">Equation 1</a> above. In fact, let's just replace the [latex]n[/latex] in that equation with the pair [latex]p[/latex]:

[latex]\Delta Z_p = 2p^2[/latex]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id="eqn2"><strong>(Equation 2)</strong></span>

The second important thing to recognize is that the atomic number [latex]Z[/latex] for the [latex]k^{\text{th}}[/latex] element is equal to the sum of all the [latex]\Delta Z[/latex] values up to and including that element, which makes sense. For example, the atomic number for xenon ([latex]k=5[/latex]) is equal to 2 + 8 + 8 + 18 + 18 = 54.

Each pair has two elements (by definition), which means that with each pair, we add [latex]2\Delta Z_p[/latex] electrons to the total. Again, the first pair is an exception, but we'll get to that. Consider the second pair, for example ([latex]k=2, 3[/latex]), which has [latex]\Delta Z_2 = 8[/latex] for each element. Taken together, this pair adds 2 * 8 = 16 electrons to the total. The third pair ([latex]k=4, 5[/latex]) has [latex]\Delta Z_3 = 18[/latex] and adds 2 * 18 = 36 electrons to the total. Then the sum of the first [latex]P[/latex] pairs is given by:

[latex]\displaystyle{\text{sum of first } P \text{ pairs} = \left(\sum\limits_{p=1}^{P}2(2p^2)\right) - 2}[/latex]

We subtract 2 to account for the fact that [latex]k=0[/latex] (from the first pair) doesn't actually contribute 2 electrons to the total. From <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faulhaber%27s_formula" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Faulhaber's formula</a> for sums of polynomial sequences, we can rewrite the sum of the quadratic sequence above as a nice cubic polynomial:

[latex]\displaystyle{\text{sum of first } P \text{ pairs} = \left(\frac{2P(P+1)(2P+1)}{3}\right) - 2}[/latex]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span id="eqn3"><strong>(Equation 3)</strong></span>

This simplifies things considerably. Then the problem becomes a matter of following these steps:

1) Choose the value of [latex]k[/latex].
2) Determine which pair [latex]p[/latex] the chosen value of [latex]k[/latex] belongs to.
3) Compute the sum of all previous pairs (up to pair [latex]p-1[/latex]) using <a href="#eqn3">Equation 3</a>.
4) Compute [latex]\Delta Z_p[/latex] for the current pair [latex]p[/latex] using <a href="#eqn2">Equation 2</a>.
5) Add either [latex]\Delta Z_p[/latex] to the subtotal from step 3 (if [latex]k[/latex] is the first element of pair [latex]p[/latex]) or [latex]2\Delta Z_p[/latex] (if [latex]k[/latex] is the second element of pair [latex]p[/latex]).

For step 2, the pair to which [latex]k[/latex] belongs is equal to 1 plus the integer division of [latex]k[/latex] into 2, i.e.:

[latex]\displaystyle{p = (k \text{ div } 2) + 1}[/latex]

Integer division refers to dropping anything beyond the decimal point and keeping only the whole numbers after division, e.g., [latex]3 \text{ div } 2 = 1[/latex]. The second to last pair [latex]p-1[/latex] is simply the equation above minus 1:

[latex]\displaystyle{p - 1 = (k \text{ div } 2)}[/latex]

For step 5, we can determine whether [latex]k[/latex] is the first or second element of pair [latex]p[/latex] with modulo division, which yields the remainder after a division operation, i.e., [latex](k \text{ mod } 2)[/latex]. This yields 0 if [latex]k[/latex] is even (making it the first element of the pair) or 1 if it's odd (making it the second element of the pair). Putting it all together:

\[ Z_k = \left(\frac{2(k \text{ div } 2)((k \text{ div } 2) + 1)(2(k \text{ div } 2) + 1)}{3}\right) - 2 + ((k \text{ mod } 2) + 1)(2((k \text{ div } 2) + 1)^2) \]

The term [latex]2((k \text{ div } 2) + 1)^2[/latex] at the end corresponds to <a href="#eqn2">Equation 2</a>, i.e., [latex]2p^2[/latex], and the preceding multiplier [latex](k \text{ mod } 2) + 1[/latex] determines whether it should be added once or twice ([latex]\Delta Z_p[/latex] or [latex]2\Delta Z_p[/latex]) based on the result of the modulo division.

And that's it! A method for directly obtaining the atomic number of the [latex]k^{\text{th}}[/latex] noble gas. How might we implement this in code? Here's an example in the form of a short Python function.

<pre><code class="language-python">def noble(k):
    prev_pairs = int((2 * (k // 2) * (k // 2 + 1) * (2 * (k // 2) + 1)) / 3) - 2
    return prev_pairs + ((k % 2 + 1) * 2 * (k // 2 + 1)**2)</code></pre>

Perhaps cryptic for someone who hasn't read this post and doesn't know how it was derived, but otherwise fairly straightforward.

<h2>Practical considerations</h2>

Like I said at the beginning of this post, there is little practical use for this—there are currently only a handful of elements in the noble gas group. As of this writing, no elements beyond 118 (oganesson) have been synthesized. This is because elements with high atomic numbers tend to be extremely unstable and live for only small fractions of a second (according to IUPAC, an atom of an element must survive for at least 10<sup>-14</sup> seconds to be considered to exist—this is the amount of time required to form an electron cloud). It's doubtful that noble gas [latex]k=8[/latex] (atomic number 168) could even exist, much less [latex]k=9[/latex] (atomic number 218). Even if atoms of these elements could exist, the quantum effects resulting from large nuclei and large electron clouds would affect the properties of these elements. I won't pretend to understand quantum chemistry or atomic forces, but these effects basically mean that superheavy elements may not follow the same trends as elements with lower atomic numbers—in other words, element 168 would not necessarily behave like a noble gas. In fact, the Wikipedia article on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_periodic_table#Elements_167_to_172">extended periodic table</a> theorizes that, in terms of behavior, element 172 would be the next noble gas (or "noble liquid," more accurately), due to these effects.

Still, it's an interesting exercise in sums and patterns that showcases some of the periodicity of the periodic table.
